1. IP (Internet protocol) Address

* Defination = Logical address assigned by network.
* Changes when device moves networks
* Assigned by network administrator or DHCP
* Used for routing across networks
* Uniqe address 
* Help to identify device

# 2 versions of IP.
1.IPV4 
* Formate: 32-bit, dotted decimal notation
* Example= 192.68.1.1 (0 to 255)range
* structure breakdown: 4 octets (8 bits each)
* 192.68.1.1

2.IPV6
* Formate: 128-bit, hexadecimal notation
* Example= 2001:0db8::1 ( 1 to 9 & a to f)range
* structure breakdown: 8 groups (16 bits each)
* 2001 : 0db8 : 0000 : 0000 : 0000 : 0000 : 0000 : 0001

## Public vs Private IP Addresses

Public IP

Definition: Globally unique address routable on internet
Example: 8.8.8.8 (Google DNS)
Use case: Servers, websites, devices accessible from internet

Private IP

Definition: Non-routable address used within private networks
Example: 192.168.1.100
Use case: Home networks, corporate LANs, internal devices

Private IP Ranges:

10.0.0.0 to 10.255.255.255 (Class A)
172.16.0.0 to 172.31.255.255 (Class B)
192.168.0.0 to 192.168.255.255 (Class C)

Static IP vs Dynamic IP Addresses

Static IP

Definition: A fixed IP address that does not change over time
Assigned by: Manually FIX configured or provided by ISP
Example: 203.0.113.10
Use case: Web servers, mail servers, remote access, VPN
Does Not change

Dynamic IP

Definition: An IP address that changes automatically over time
Assigned by: DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) server
Example: 192.168.1.5 → may change later to 192.168.1.20
Use case: Home users, mobile networks, general internet browsing
chnage when reconnecting

2. MAC (Media Access Control) Address

* Defination = Physical address burned into hardware
* Permanent and unique to device
* Never changes
* Used for local network communication
